b"\xe2\x80\x9cCan technology help a blind runner navigate?\xe2\x80\x9d That\xe2\x80\x99s what Thomas Panek, an avid runner and CEO of @guidingeyes, asked during a 2019 hackathon. b"To celebrate 30 years of the Americans with Disabilities Act, we asked Googlers what the #ADA30 means to them. 

\xe2\x80\x9cEvery school I\xe2\x80\x99ve been allowed to attend, every job I\xe2\x80\x99ve been accepted to, every time I have entered a room and been the first one like me to enter that room\xe2\x80\x94I've had all these opportunities because my Disabled elders fought to ensure the #ADA. In short, I owe them my life.

\xe2\x80\x9cThe ADA reminds us that access is our right. Access is our civil right. Access is our human right. Disabled people said it, the ADA validates it, and now and every day, it\xe2\x80\x99s up to each of us to act on it.

\xe2\x80\x9cAs we reflect on how far we\xe2\x80\x99ve gotten, I want us to imagine how much further we can go. What would it be like to live in a world that not only accepts Disabled people, but loves us?\xe2\x80\x9d says Googler @aubrieality. Watch today\xe2\x80\x99s story to hear from other Googlers, and tap the link in bio to learn about how Google is striving to make the world more accessible for all."
